5s5.title: Operations in Set theory

5s8.title: Union
5s8.clickbait: The union of two sets is the set of elements which are in one or the other, or both
5s8.text:
The union of two sets $A$ and $B$, denoted $A \cup B$, is the set of things which are either in $A$ or in $B$ or both.

![illustration of the output of the union operation](https://imgh.us/set_union.svg)

Formally stated, where $C = A \cup B$

$$x \in C \leftrightarrow (x \in A \lor x \in B)$$

That is, [46m] $x$ is in the union $C$, then either $x$ is in $A$ or $B$ or possibly both.

%%todo: more lengthy explanation for [1r6] level%%

# Examples

 - $\{1,2\} \cup \{2,3\} = \{1,2,3\}$
 - $\{1,2\} \cup \{8,9\} = \{1,2,8,9\}$
 - $\{0,2,4,6\} \cup \{3,4,5,6\} = \{0,2,3,4,5,6\}$
 - $\mathbb{R^-} \cup \mathbb{R^+} \cup \{0\} = \mathbb{R}$ (In other words, the union of the negative reals, the positive reals and zero make up all of the [4bc real numbers].)
